webpackJsonp([73],{352:function(e,o){e.exports={data:{config:{siteMetadata:{title:"Bricolage",author:"Kyle Mathews"}},markdown:{id:"/Users/kylemathews/programs/blog/pages/2007-07-02---purple-cow-erratum/index.md",bodyHTML:'<p>I\'ve been reading <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Purple-Cow-Transform-Business-Remarkable/dp/159184021X">"Purple Cow"</a> by <a href="http://sethgodin.typepad.com/">Seth Godin</a> lately and am loving it. I read one of the case studies in the book today and found it quite funny in light of the <a href="http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&#x26;sid=aKtbJPOEkO.U">500,000 iPhones Apple sold last Friday</a>.</p>\n<p>He wrote:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<h3>Case Study: Motorola and Nokia</h3>\n<p>Guess what? Cell phones are now boring. Just about everyone who needs a phone now has one. Most people who want a phone have one, too. The companies that built that revolution now have a problem: What next?What do they have to put into a phone to get people to notice it? Is it possible to make a remarkable phone anymore?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It\'s obvious now that Apple has figured out how to make a remarkable phone with its iPhone, a purple cow worthy phone, while Nokia and Motorola have not.</p>\n<p>Perhaps it\'s time for Seth to update his case study?</p>\n',frontmatter:{readNext:null,title:"Purple Cow Erratum",tags:["internet-marketing"],date:"July 02, 2007"}}},pathContext:{path:"/purple-cow-erratum/",component:"/Users/kylemathews/programs/blog/pages/blog-post.js"}}}});
//# sourceMappingURL=73.path---purple-cow-erratum-9943a4a99fb0ef7c27a0.js.map